  "answer": "The critic misreads the standard. Clause (2) requires that forbidden cases be concrete observations that could realistically obtain, not that they be phrased as positive records. Forbidden case 1 specifies a concrete, observable archival pattern — the absence of debt-crisis correspondence in the Ugarit archives — which is precisely the kind of datable documentary evidence that could realistically be found if the proposed debt-credit mechanism were operative. Forbidden case 2 is not vague: it identifies a specific, archaeologically observable pattern — regional autarky in material culture (e.g., local ceramic production sequences, absence of non-local raw materials in workshop debris, isotopic sourcing of metals) — that would be a concrete, datable counterexample to the claimed specialization. Forbidden case 3 is not a mere negative claim; it identifies a concrete evidentiary scenario — Egyptian textual and archaeological records showing equal dependence on Levantine timber and incense without evidence of domestic substitution — that is directly observable in the well-preserved Egyptian record. All three forbidden cases describe patterns of evidence that could realistically be found in the archaeological and textual record, satisfying the requirement for concrete, obtainable observations."
